-Hey, Steve.
-Hey, Chuck.

153
00:11:00,910 --> 00:11:02,605
What are you working on?

154
00:11:04,480 --> 00:11:08,280
The piece Gabriel García Márquez
wrote about the FalkIands war.

155
00:11:08,751 --> 00:11:10,309
How about you?

156
00:11:13,155 --> 00:11:16,283
Young Republicans
at the CPAC conference.

157
00:11:16,492 --> 00:11:18,221
Pretty standard stuff.

158
00:11:18,427 --> 00:11:22,363
Hotel ballrooms, boring speeches,
chicken dinners.

159
00:11:26,903 --> 00:11:30,270
Which is why everybody spends
their time in the suites upstairs...

160
00:11:30,473 --> 00:11:32,168
...committing felonies.

161
00:11:33,109 --> 00:11:34,303
Oh, yeah?

162
00:11:35,177 --> 00:11:37,805
Yeah, l went to one.
The ballroom is empty.

163
00:11:38,014 --> 00:11:39,845
Every delegate under the age of 25...

164
00:11:40,049 --> 00:11:42,244
...was up on the fifth floor
getting loaded.

165
00:11:42,451 --> 00:11:46,046
Drugs, binge drinking, hookers....
Gets pretty ugly.

166
00:11:48,291 --> 00:11:51,351
-Sounds great, Steve.
-So does yours.

167
00:11:53,596 --> 00:11:56,030
Okay, well.... l gotta get back to work.

168
00:11:56,232 --> 00:11:58,962
-Have a good lunch.
-Thanks.

169
00:11:59,502 --> 00:12:03,871
Hold it. l have to give myself
a demerit for poor scene-setting.

170
00:12:04,073 --> 00:12:06,837
Let me explain. A year ago,
Chuck Iane and l were peers.

171
00:12:07,043 --> 00:12:08,442
He hadn't become editor yet.

172
00:12:08,644 --> 00:12:11,010
Michael Kelly was editing
the magazine then.

173
00:12:11,213 --> 00:12:14,376
Sorry, Mrs. Duke.
l know how you feel about clarity.

174
00:12:21,190 --> 00:12:23,522
We've gotta start
calling some other places.

175
00:12:23,726 --> 00:12:26,559
l don't think l can
eat this stuff every day.

176
00:12:27,363 --> 00:12:30,821
it was the Cannon Building.
You had it as Russell. l fixed it.

177
00:12:31,033 --> 00:12:32,227
Thank you.

178
00:12:32,435 --> 00:12:35,233
-l really liked it, Ames.
-But boring, right?

179
00:12:38,174 --> 00:12:40,665
No, l really, really liked it.

180
00:12:42,545 --> 00:12:45,378
-Yes, dear?
-Somebody for you on three.

181
00:12:45,581 --> 00:12:46,946
Someone from Harper's.

182
00:12:47,249 --> 00:12:51,083
-When did you start talking to them?
-I'm not. it's probably nothing.

183
00:12:51,287 --> 00:12:53,118
-Send it to my voice mail.
-Very good.

184
00:12:53,322 --> 00:12:56,723
By the way, Glo,
that lipstick is the bomb.

185
00:12:57,660 --> 00:12:58,854
Thanks, doll.

186
00:12:59,061 --> 00:13:00,995
What is it, Midnight Mist?

187
00:13:04,133 --> 00:13:06,567
-l really got to stop doing that.
-What?

188
00:13:06,769 --> 00:13:09,738
All l do is give people
more reasons to assume I'm gay.

189
00:13:10,306 --> 00:13:12,206
l mean, lately, it's everyone.

190
00:13:12,408 --> 00:13:15,468
The other night, l went to dinner
with this guy from The Post.

191
00:13:15,678 --> 00:13:18,545
-Who?
-l can't tell you. He made me promise.

192
00:13:18,748 --> 00:13:20,443
We're walking around afterwards...

193
00:13:20,649 --> 00:13:23,277
...talking about Medicare
for God's sakes.

194
00:13:23,486 --> 00:13:28,253
Then, the next thing l know, we're
standing on the corner of 18th and T...

195
00:13:29,191 --> 00:13:33,389
...and he somehow managed to slip
his tongue down my throat.

196
00:13:35,297 --> 00:13:38,528
And I'm like, ''Wait a minute,
how'd this happen?''

197
00:13:40,036 --> 00:13:43,005
-l don't understand.
-Yeah, neither did l.

198
00:13:44,173 --> 00:13:46,107
-Hey.
-Michael.

199
00:13:46,308 --> 00:13:47,536
-Got a minute?
-Of course.

200
00:13:47,743 --> 00:13:50,303
We have a problem with
the ''Spring Breakdown'' piece.

201
00:13:50,513 --> 00:13:53,641
Just got a letter from David Keene.
He ran the CPAC conference.

202
00:13:53,849 --> 00:13:56,010
-He's made some--
-Are you mad at me?

203
00:13:57,119 --> 00:14:00,646
He's made some pretty serious
charges. We need to answer them.

204
00:14:00,856 --> 00:14:04,986
Okay. My notes are at home. l can be
back in 20 minutes. is that too long?

205
00:14:05,194 --> 00:14:08,789
Do your notes have anything
about the minibars? That would help.

206
00:14:08,998 --> 00:14:11,796
l think so. No, I'm sure. Why?

207
00:14:12,034 --> 00:14:15,629
He claims the Omni Shoreham
doesn't even have minibars.

208
00:14:16,138 --> 00:14:20,302
l saw them. No, there were little
bottles of booze all over the room.

209
00:14:20,743 --> 00:14:25,874
Okay. I'll get Aaron and Rob into it
and start the fact-check again.

210
00:14:26,082 --> 00:14:28,380
-I'll get my notes.
-Thank you.

211
00:14:29,151 --> 00:14:31,312
I'm sorry, we'll have to finish this later.

212
00:14:31,520 --> 00:14:34,216
No, no, l understand. Thank you.

213
00:14:48,537 --> 00:14:49,799
What's wrong?

214
00:14:53,275 --> 00:14:54,469
Just tell me.

215
00:14:56,278 --> 00:14:57,802
Keene was right, Michael.

216
00:15:02,751 --> 00:15:06,847
l messed up. l made a huge error.

217
00:15:16,332 --> 00:15:19,665
l don't know what to say.
lf you want me to resign, l will.

218
00:15:19,869 --> 00:15:22,269
l want you to tell me what happened.

219
00:15:26,275 --> 00:15:28,937
They don't have minibars
at the Omni Shoreham Hotel.

220
00:15:30,779 --> 00:15:34,579
l guess l just saw all those little
bottles and l made an assumption...

221
00:15:34,783 --> 00:15:38,048
...which l know we're never
supposed to do.

222
00:15:38,621 --> 00:15:39,918
I'm really sorry.

223
00:15:43,425 --> 00:15:48,920
Those guys were drinking out
of a rented refrigerator, a mini-fridge.

224
00:15:49,598 --> 00:15:52,089
-That's it?
-Yeah.

225
00:15:52,334 --> 00:15:55,667
-The rest of the piece is solid?
-Well, yeah, of course.

226
00:15:56,305 --> 00:15:59,206
Go home, Steve.
Your resignation will not be required.

227
00:15:59,642 --> 00:16:03,078
-Really? You're not mad?
-Of course not.

228
00:16:05,014 --> 00:16:08,381
-Do you want my notes?
-Have a good night.

229
00:16:13,756 --> 00:16:15,553
Thanks, Michael.

230
00:16:16,192 --> 00:16:17,386
Thanks for backing me.

231
00:16:18,294 --> 00:16:19,921
it's what editors do.

232
00:16:23,832 --> 00:16:25,060
Good night.

233
00:16:47,223 --> 00:16:49,418
Hi. Front desk, please.

234
00:16:51,927 --> 00:16:53,554
Hi, l need some information.

235
00:16:53,762 --> 00:16:56,856
Do the suites at your hotels
have minibars?

236
00:16:57,933 --> 00:17:00,197
Well, can a guest
rent something like that...

237
00:17:00,402 --> 00:17:02,700
...like a mini-refrigerator
or something?

238
00:17:03,138 --> 00:17:04,435
They can.

239
00:17:04,673 --> 00:17:06,766
