00:49:02,422 --> 00:49:06,449
...without first understanding how a
piece gets edited at a place like TNR.

695
00:49:06,660 --> 00:49:09,788
This is the system Michael Kelly
brought from The New Yorker...

696
00:49:09,997 --> 00:49:11,726
...a three-day torture test.

697
00:49:11,932 --> 00:49:14,298
lf your article's good,
it'll make it better.

698
00:49:14,601 --> 00:49:18,332
lf your article's shaky,
you're in for a long week.

699
00:49:18,705 --> 00:49:21,105
A story comes in,
and it goes to a senior editor.

700
00:49:21,308 --> 00:49:23,469
He or she edits it on computer...

701
00:49:23,677 --> 00:49:25,941
...then calls in the writer
to make revisions.

702
00:49:26,146 --> 00:49:29,377
Then it goes to a second editor,
and the writer revises it again.

703
00:49:29,583 --> 00:49:32,245
Then it goes through a fact-check,
where every fact...

704
00:49:32,452 --> 00:49:37,048
...every date, every title, every place
or assertion is checked and verified.

705
00:49:37,257 --> 00:49:40,784
Then it goes to a copy editor,
where it is scrutinized once again.

706
00:49:40,994 --> 00:49:43,895
Then it goes to lawyers
who apply their burdens of proof.

707
00:49:44,097 --> 00:49:45,291
Marty looks at it too.

708
00:49:45,499 --> 00:49:48,024
He's concerned with any comment
the magazine makes.

709
00:49:48,235 --> 00:49:50,999
Then production lays it out
in column inches and type.

